534
00:33:42,987 --> 00:33:44,545
Brainstorming?

535
00:33:44,655 --> 00:33:45,986
Sorry I missed that.

536
00:33:46,090 --> 00:33:47,648
What was the line?

537
00:33:47,759 --> 00:33:49,386
A bucket of kisses.

538
00:33:49,494 --> 00:33:50,688
Basket of kisses.

539
00:33:50,795 --> 00:33:51,693
Bucket sounds better.

540
00:33:51,796 --> 00:33:53,263
If you like 'em wet and sloppy.

541
00:33:54,298 --> 00:33:55,458
The point is,

542
00:33:55,566 --> 00:33:58,501
while the rest of the hens were busy
pulling out each other's feathers,

543
00:33:58,603 --> 00:34:00,594
that one saw the benefit, not the feature.

544
00:34:00,705 --> 00:34:02,070
Really?

545
00:34:02,173 --> 00:34:05,768
Yeah. She said she didn't want to be one
of a hundred colors in a box.

546
00:34:08,046 --> 00:34:09,707
That's interesting, isn't it?

547
00:34:09,814 --> 00:34:12,214
It is.

548
00:34:12,316 --> 00:34:16,047
It was like watching a dog play the piano.

549
00:34:26,364 --> 00:34:27,922
<i>It's me, Barbara. Can you talk?</i>

550
00:34:28,032 --> 00:34:29,966
She's still sleeping, thank God.

551
00:34:30,068 --> 00:34:31,160
What's on your mind?

552
00:34:31,269 --> 00:34:34,238
I think I might have met somebody.

553
00:34:34,338 --> 00:34:37,171
You're not sure? That's good.

554
00:34:37,275 --> 00:34:40,301
He has some serious limitations.

555
00:34:40,411 --> 00:34:41,810
<i>Does he work in the store?</i>

556
00:34:41,913 --> 00:34:44,108
No, he doesn't work at the store.

557
00:34:44,215 --> 00:34:45,842
He has a job, doesn't he?

558
00:34:45,950 --> 00:34:47,247
<i>Yes.</i>

559
00:34:47,351 --> 00:34:48,613
Then what's the problem?

560
00:34:48,719 --> 00:34:50,243
Would Daddy like him?

561
00:34:51,722 --> 00:34:52,916
Daddy would hate him.

562
00:34:53,024 --> 00:34:54,651
So he's not Jewish.

563
00:34:58,362 --> 00:34:59,522
<i>Who cares what Daddy thinks?</i>

564
00:34:59,630 --> 00:35:02,326
He's not your boyfriend anymore.

565
00:35:02,433 --> 00:35:03,491
Barbara.

566
00:35:03,601 --> 00:35:04,795
<i>You're 28 years old.</i>

567
00:35:04,902 --> 00:35:06,164
<i>You work 60 hours a week.</i>

568
00:35:06,270 --> 00:35:08,602
The last thing you want
is to end up like Aunt Rosie,

569
00:35:08,706 --> 00:35:10,867
lying to your nieces about
how many engagements you had.

570
00:35:10,975 --> 00:35:12,806
Aunt Rosie wasn't lying.

571
00:35:12,910 --> 00:35:15,037
Oh, please, there was
no Max the Communist.

572
00:35:15,146 --> 00:35:17,307
<i>Does he have all his hair?</i>

573
00:35:17,415 --> 00:35:18,746
More than he'll ever need.

574
00:35:18,850 --> 00:35:20,340
<i>Is he funny?</i>

575
00:35:20,451 --> 00:35:23,420
Sometimes. After a couple.

576
00:35:23,521 --> 00:35:26,854
<i>So he's a shikker. Daddy will hate him.</i>

577
00:35:26,958 --> 00:35:30,394
I do feel this attraction.

578
00:35:30,495 --> 00:35:31,689
I want him,

579
00:35:31,796 --> 00:35:33,889
and I want to ignore
everything else about him.

580
00:35:33,998 --> 00:35:36,489
<i>It's 1960. We don't live in a shtetl.</i>

581
00:35:36,601 --> 00:35:37,727
We can marry for love.

582
00:35:37,835 --> 00:35:40,702
I'm not sure people do that anymore.

583
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:43,296
<i>Why do you always have to be so cynical?</i>

584
00:35:45,643 --> 00:35:49,579
Because sometimes...
things come...

585
00:35:49,680 --> 00:35:50,738
good things...

586
00:35:50,848 --> 00:35:52,475
but there's no future in them.

587
00:35:52,583 --> 00:35:53,880
<i>You're a modern woman, Rach.</i>

588
00:35:53,985 --> 00:35:55,714
<i>Forget the wedding.</i>

589
00:35:55,820 --> 00:35:58,846
Believe me, I'd do anything
for some romance right now.

590
00:36:08,699 --> 00:36:09,791
Peggy.

591
00:36:09,901 --> 00:36:11,391
Hi, Joan.

592
00:36:12,637 --> 00:36:15,936
Mr. Rumsen would like you
to put your industrious little mind

593
00:36:16,040 --> 00:36:18,565
towards coming up with copy
for Belle Jolie Lipsticks.

594
00:36:20,645 --> 00:36:21,543
I don't understand.

595
00:36:21,646 --> 00:36:23,045
They want me to write something?

596
00:36:23,147 --> 00:36:24,910
Whatever you said
in that brainstorming session

597
00:36:25,016 --> 00:36:27,041
apparently knocked their socks off.

598
00:36:28,186 --> 00:36:30,154
Oh, my gosh.

599
00:36:30,254 --> 00:36:31,585
I don't know what to say.

600
00:36:31,689 --> 00:36:34,157
You will, of course,
continue to cover Mr. Draper's desk.

601
00:36:34,258 --> 00:36:36,886
Any writing you do
will be on your own time.

602
00:36:36,994 --> 00:36:38,086
Do I get a raise?

603
00:36:38,196 --> 00:36:39,288
No.

604
00:36:39,397 --> 00:36:40,329
Congratulations.

605
00:36:40,431 --> 00:36:43,423
More work and more responsibility.

606
00:36:43,534 --> 00:36:46,332
I guess you'll be entitled
to some dinner money.

607
00:36:46,437 --> 00:36:48,098
That's swell.

608
00:36:48,206 --> 00:36:49,696
Maybe I should go and thank them?

609
00:36:50,975 --> 00:36:53,409
I'm not really dressed.
Tomorrow, maybe?

610
00:36:53,511 --> 00:36:55,604
No need.
They wanted me to tell you.

611
00:36:55,713 --> 00:36:57,237
They were very specific about it.

612
00:36:58,516 --> 00:37:02,179
Well, you know what they say:
The medium is the message.

613
00:37:18,769 --> 00:37:22,728
And here I was just wishing for a man
to help me with my yard work.

614
00:37:31,148 --> 00:37:32,615
Sorry.

615
00:37:32,717 --> 00:37:35,811
That's what I get for being domestic.

616
00:37:35,920 --> 00:37:38,320
Let's get this off.

617
00:37:41,659 --> 00:37:43,991
Oh, God, hold that.

618
00:37:44,095 --> 00:37:45,392
The thought.

619
00:37:57,675 --> 00:37:58,699
Hi, Roy.

620
00:37:58,809 --> 00:38:00,299
Hi, beautiful.

621
00:38:01,946 --> 00:38:03,607
What's shakin'?

622
00:38:07,752 --> 00:38:09,617
Busy dance card, huh?

623
00:38:09,720 --> 00:38:12,655
Uh, Roy, this is my friend Don Draper.

624
00:38:12,757 --> 00:38:14,987
Don, this is Roy Hazellit.

625
00:38:15,092 --> 00:38:16,081
Pleasure.

626
00:38:17,728 --> 00:38:19,127
Lan's playing down at the Gaslight.

627
00:38:19,230 --> 00:38:20,788
We're gonna go support him,
pass the basket.

628
00:38:20,898 --> 00:38:22,866
You in?

629
00:38:22,967 --> 00:38:24,696
That is if Dad will let you out.

630
00:38:24,802 --> 00:38:26,099
Sounds like fun.

631
00:38:26,203 --> 00:38:28,194
Don, we should go down for a while.

632
00:38:28,306 --> 00:38:30,035
Come on. It'll be a kick.
What do you say?

633
00:38:30,141 --> 00:38:32,006
Afraid you'll miss the 5:31?

634
00:38:34,612 --> 00:38:35,909
I think I'm gonna stay here.

635
00:38:42,353 --> 00:38:46,346
I'll wear a skirt and nothing else.

636
00:38:53,064 --> 00:38:54,429
What took you so long?

637
00:38:54,532 --> 00:38:57,194
One of the media buyers
ambushed me in the elevator

638
00:38:57,301 --> 00:38:59,769
with tickets to the ballet, of all things.

639
00:38:59,870 --> 00:39:01,235
I told him I had plans,

640
00:39:01,339 --> 00:39:03,273
but he insisted we share
a cab across town anyways.

641
00:39:03,441 --> 00:39:04,373
I couldn't shake him.

642
00:39:04,475 --> 00:39:05,373
Which one was it?

643
00:39:05,476 --> 00:39:08,536
George Asbury. He's a hound.

644
00:39:08,646 --> 00:39:11,809
It doesn't matter.
They're all just boys.

645
00:39:11,916 --> 00:39:13,907
Poor bastard probably
couldn't help himself,

646
00:39:14,018 --> 00:39:18,079
the way you glide around that office
like some magnificent ship.

647
00:39:19,724 --> 00:39:22,158
Well, I don't want to be a distraction.

648
00:39:22,259 --> 00:39:26,320
Shall I, um, order horse blinders
for the rest of the office?

649
00:39:30,134 --> 00:39:32,967
You didn't.

650
00:39:33,070 --> 00:39:34,901
Oh, I sure did.

651
00:39:40,978 --> 00:39:44,379
Well, what am I supposed to do with it?

652
00:39:44,482 --> 00:39:47,815
The store lady said you can do anything
but put the cage on the radiator.

653
00:39:47,918 --> 00:39:49,977
You're terrible.

654
00:39:50,087 --> 00:39:52,521
Well, you can't blame a man for trying.

655
00:39:52,623 --> 00:39:55,649
I just hate the thought
of having to share you.

656
00:39:57,061 --> 00:40:00,326
You don't have to share me now.

657
00:40:06,404 --> 00:40:08,895
Joanie, you smell so good.

658
00:40:09,006 --> 00:40:11,497
I've been thinking about this all day.

659
00:40:11,609 --> 00:40:16,603
Mona is looking at a weekend
in Old Saybrook with the in-laws.

660
00:40:16,714 --> 00:40:19,376
There's not enough liquor in the world.

661
00:40:21,786 --> 00:40:23,185
Roger.

662
00:40:29,360 --> 00:40:30,759
Sorry.

663
